00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:21.260
calendar in the yearly,
monthly and daily basis.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:26.670
The first one is yearly cycle.

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:30.850
For a character based
game like Monster Strike,

00:08:30.850 --> 00:08:32.500
the best content
for monetization

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:35.169
is always additional
legendary character

00:08:35.169 --> 00:08:40.230
which has significant
skills and parameters.

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:45.230
So Mixi basically runs this
type of flagship, heavy LiveOps

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:49.110
gacha events every three months,
considering the seasonality

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:50.820
and so on.

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:52.890
According to Mixi,
the once in three

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:56.250
months is kind of a magic
number from their four years'

00:08:56.250 --> 00:09:00.620
experience, because if users
are exposed too frequently

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:05.240
to this type of heavy events,
they get tired of catching up,

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.960
and they eventually
leave the game.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:09.930
So rather than increasing the
number of these heavy LiveOps

00:09:09.930 --> 00:09:14.922
events, Mixi rather focuses on
maximizing the revenue spike

00:09:14.922 --> 00:09:15.630
for each of them.

00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:20.650
And zooming into
the monthly cycle,

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:23.450
Monster Strike generally
has a consistent beat

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:27.050
of revenue spike in
a bi-weekly basis.

00:09:27.050 --> 00:09:29.810
This is because
they are following

00:09:29.810 --> 00:09:32.870
the first day of the month spike
tradition in the Japan market,

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:36.260
and also place a mid-size
LiveOps is in between these,

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:39.380
to keep your core users engaged.

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:41.560
Precisely speaking, they
are actually running

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:45.040
a lot of other events in between
these, but that they stick

00:09:45.040 --> 00:09:47.830
to this cadence with
a strong gacha event

00:09:47.830 --> 00:09:50.140
to keep the good
rhythm of excitement

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:53.080
for their core users,
which is especially

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:54.100
for the paying users.

00:09:56.940 --> 00:09:59.610
And they also care
a lot about when

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:01.860
to deploy, what kind
of events in a day,

00:10:01.860 --> 00:10:04.200
from the relevancy
point of view.

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:08.160
For example, they deploy
the gacha events typically

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:12.900
around lunchtime, because
they want their users who just

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:14.550
got a new character
through the gacha,

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:16.580
to show off that to
your real friends

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:18.080
who are eating their
lunch together,

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:20.910
and who hopefully play
the game together.

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:23.510
And on the other hand,
regarding the quests that

00:10:23.510 --> 00:10:26.400
require some level
of concentration,

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:31.050
they typical deploy these around
commit time, or after dinner,

00:10:31.050 --> 00:10:33.390
when users typically
play the game alone

00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:35.770
with a lot of concentration.

00:10:35.770 --> 00:10:40.170
So in these ways Mixi is
carefully designing the LiveOps

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:43.140
calendar to help
their users enjoy

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:47.020
surfing on the various sides
of the webs of the LiveOps.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.530
So now let's do a bit more deep
dive into one of the flagship

00:10:54.530 --> 00:10:59.440
LiveOps events, which happens
only once in three months.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:02.260
The example here is
a special gacha event

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:04.590
which featured the new
legendary character called

00:11:04.590 --> 00:11:07.300
Pandora, this cute girl.

00:11:07.300 --> 00:11:11.506
And this event was especially
successful for Mixi

00:11:11.506 --> 00:11:16.390
because it drove 150% year
over year increase in revenue.

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:19.495
So let's take a look at Mixi's
efforts behind this big moment.

00:11:22.190 --> 00:11:25.190
The first one is quantity
control of in-game currencies

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:28.190
owned by users.

00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:30.989
When you have a
huge monetization

00:11:30.989 --> 00:11:32.655
moment in your game
in terms of LiveOps,

00:11:32.655 --> 00:11:35.595
it is very important
to create an idea

00:11:35.595 --> 00:11:40.010
of the status of the
in-game economy beforehand.

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:42.440
For example, if
users have too many

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:44.630
unconsumed in-game
currencies already,

00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:47.210
they just spend these
when LiveOps come in,

00:11:47.210 --> 00:11:49.130
and they don't really
purchase new IAP,

00:11:49.130 --> 00:11:52.612
which could be a problem
for your monetization.

00:11:52.612 --> 00:11:56.320
So Mixi actually tracks the
quantity of in-game currency

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:58.920
that is owned by users as
one of the key metrics,

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:03.210
and accumulated a small LiveOps
before the flagship gacha

00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:07.350
event, and created an ideal
or state of in-game economy

00:12:07.350 --> 00:12:11.440
prior to that big monetization
moment for the game.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:14.740
And also they went
beyond in-game operations

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:18.970
and added out of the
game, media mix activities

00:12:18.970 --> 00:12:21.640
to promote the LiveOps event.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:24.160
For example, this
character Pandora

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:28.660
was introduced first in the
YouTube anime of Monster Strike

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:31.120
three days before the
actual in-game event,

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:33.820
