and out of game
marketing activities,

00:14:02.790 --> 00:14:06.390
they could achieve the
beautiful reshaped recovery

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:09.360
of monthly active
users, and it resulted

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:13.110
in the great financial success
of the Pandora gacha event

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:15.270
after that.

00:14:15.270 --> 00:14:17.700
When talking about
LiveOps, people

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:20.610
tend to focus too much on
just the in-game activities,

00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:24.100
but actually it drives to
more impact on your business

00:14:24.100 --> 00:14:28.420
it's nicely branded with out
of game marketing activities.

00:14:28.420 --> 00:14:32.460
So this is a very
good example, I think.

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:35.560
So that was the Pandora
gacha event example.

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:39.160
And let me talk about
some other cases as well.

00:14:39.160 --> 00:14:42.880
When talking about Japan's
unique LiveOps culture,

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:45.430
IP collaboration is
something I cannot ignore,

00:14:45.430 --> 00:14:48.370
which is very popular
among Japanese developers.

00:14:48.370 --> 00:14:53.390
For example, collaboration with
popular games' IP, comic IP,

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:57.430
anime IP, is very popular
among Japanese games,

00:14:57.430 --> 00:15:01.090
because it is very effective
to bring the new surprise

00:15:01.090 --> 00:15:04.420
to your existing
audience base, and also

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:07.020
reach out to the entirely
new audience space

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:09.010
through the power
of the different IP.

00:15:11.810 --> 00:15:14.810
And this kind of
collaboration can also

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:18.320
happen with non-game
offline brands as well.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:21.940
This is my favorite example,
but Monster Strike actually

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:24.680
collaborated with
Baskin-Robbins [INAUDIBLE],,

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:28.610
a popular ice cream franchise
store, and they actually

00:15:28.610 --> 00:15:31.070
created a special
quest in the game,

00:15:31.070 --> 00:15:33.950
and the when users
completed the quest,

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:37.190
they could get a free ice
cream coupon inside the game.

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:42.010
And if I'm not biased, everyone
loves ice cream, right?

00:15:42.010 --> 00:15:44.150
So actually Monster
Strike could make

00:15:44.150 --> 00:15:46.700
their users happy by
giving away free ice cream,

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:50.480
and in return, Baskin-Robbins
could drive the actual people

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:54.080
to the store, and even
enhance their brand awareness

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:55.700
with this.

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:57.520
This case is quite
interesting to me,

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:01.500
because it shows me how wide
the scope of LiveOps is.

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:03.850
If it makes sense for
you and your partner,

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:07.060
you can even distribute your
ice cream through your users

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:08.410
in the context of LiveOps.

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:13.390
So that was the Mixi case.

00:16:13.390 --> 00:16:16.150
And I'd like to introduce
you to another case,

00:16:16.150 --> 00:16:18.910
from the other Japanese
developer, KLab,

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:23.010
and the game is
BLEACH: Brave Souls.

00:16:23.010 --> 00:16:26.350
When designing LiveOps,
taking a data driven approach

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:28.810
is really effective
and important.

00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:31.650
So here I'd like to
introduce to you how

00:16:31.650 --> 00:16:34.790
sophisticated developers
at KLab are designing

00:16:34.790 --> 00:16:38.960
effective LiveOps, based
on the insights gained

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:40.800
through the in-game
data log analytics.

00:16:43.550 --> 00:16:47.320
This slide shows the basic
KPIs that the KLab analytics

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:51.810
team is looking at, which
includes monetization KPI,

00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:55.280
[INAUDIBLE] revenue, and the
ARPPU, and engagement KPIs,

00:16:55.280 --> 00:16:58.040
like churn rate, and
the new user KPIs,

00:16:58.040 --> 00:17:02.180
including installs and
seven-day retention.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:05.680
To extract key insights, the
KLab analytics team actually

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:09.440
look at these KPIs from four
different user segmentation

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:12.140
angles, which includes
in game status,

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:16.460
install timing, login
frequency, and spend range.

00:17:16.460 --> 00:17:19.790
Here I'd like to introduce to
you one interesting case, where

00:17:19.790 --> 00:17:23.540
a KLab team found very good
insight looking at the in game

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:28.150
status segmentation.

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:32.500
So BLEACH: Brave Souls has a
character build-up function,

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:34.270
called a skill board.

00:17:34.270 --> 00:17:37.750
And the KLab team found that the
combination of this skill board

00:17:37.750 --> 00:17:40.870
progression and the maximum
rarity of the character

00:17:40.870 --> 00:17:44.050
that the users own is actually
one of the best angles

00:17:44.050 --> 00:17:48.970
to look at the health status
of the overall in-game balance.

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:52.690
When they look at
key engagement KPIs

00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:54.940
from this user
segmentation angle,

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:58.650
they found that the users
who own the six-star rarity

00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:02.500
character, but hasn't completed
the skill board yet, actually

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:04.540
has a significant
churn rate compared

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:08.020
with other groups of users.

00:18:08.020 --> 00:18:10.330
And even worse,
this group of people

00:18:10.330 --> 00:18:14.380
represented over 20%
of the total consumer

00:18:14.380 --> 00:18:15.620
spend for this game.

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:19.270
So it was a problem.

00:18:19.270 --> 00:18:23.270
So to solve this problem,
KLab added new quests

00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:26.000
that helped users to complete
the six-star still board

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.110
easily.

00:18:27.110 --> 00:18:30.380
And by doing so, the users
who complete the skill board

00:18:30.380 --> 00:18:32.420
and go up to the
next level actually

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:36.890
increased from 4% to
9.7% month over month.

00:18:36.890 --> 00:18:39.800
And even significantly,
the churn rate

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:43.520
of this specific group
decreased by 11.8%,

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:46.640
compared from the
previous months.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:49.090
As I said, this group
of users represented

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:52.280
the 20% of the total
consumer spend, so now you

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:55.700
see how impactful it was for
the BLEACH: Brave Souls team.

00:18:59.070 --> 00:19:02.510
So it was quick, but I hope
you enjoyed some fresh case

00:19:02.510 --> 00:19:05.850
studies shared from the
Mixi and the KLab teams.

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:09.950
So now I'd like to summarize
today's key takeaways

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:11.000
from these case studies.

00:19:13.710 --> 00:19:17.560
So here's four key
pillars I talked today.

00:19:17.560 --> 00:19:20.490
The first one is LiveOps design.

00:19:20.490 --> 00:19:23.300
So if you want to make
the most out of LiveOps,

00:19:23.300 --> 00:19:26.760
you have to design your
game with LiveOps in mind.

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:29.360
I think Mixi's system
event functionality

00:19:29.360 --> 00:19:32.530
is one of the great
examples of doing this.

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:36.030
And also, you have to design
a strategic cycle of LiveOps,

00:19:36.030 --> 00:19:38.120
if you would like to
run a lot of LiveOps.

00:19:38.120 --> 00:19:41.980
Otherwise your users get
swamped by the flood of LiveOps.

00:19:41.980 --> 00:19:44.230
And also the control
of in-game economy,

00:19:44.230 --> 00:19:45.680
which is very important.

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:48.300
So you shouldn't
forget about it.

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:51.670
And the third, go
beyond simple LiveOps.

00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:53.590
When talking about
LiveOps, people

00:19:53.590 --> 00:19:56.930
tend to focus too much on
just in-game activities.

00:19:56.930 --> 00:19:59.620
But when it's nicely
branded with out of the game

00:19:59.620 --> 00:20:03.040
marketing activities, you can
actually generate more impact

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:05.070
on your business.

00:20:05.070 --> 00:20:07.920
And the collaboration
with other IPs and brands

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:09.810
could be an interesting
idea for you,

00:20:09.810 --> 00:20:15.000
if you want to reach out to an
entirely new audience space.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:18.570
And lastly, user
behavior is always

00:20:18.570 --> 00:20:20.160
a great source of insights.

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:23.670
So if you want to be really
effective and efficient

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:27.030
in creating new LiveOps
events for your game,

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:29.760
taking a data driven approach
would work pretty well for you.

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:33.180
OK.

00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:34.710
So thanks for listening.

